<subSubSection id="CEF66D9FFF8EB25CFCD5FA08FD60FD66" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="720" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" type="description">
<paragraph id="86533E14FF8EB252FCD5FA08FBBEFA34" blockId="7.[826,1055,1436,1458]" box="[826,1055,1436,1458]" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF8EB252FCD5FA08FBBEFA34" box="[826,1055,1436,1458]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">
Description (
<figureCitation id="1ED72291FF8EB252FC27FA08FBB6FA34" box="[968,1047,1436,1458]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="8.[142,220,1579,1598]" captionTargetBox="[303,1259,197,1547]" captionTargetId="figure-161@8.[302,1262,196,1547]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 3. Male internal reproductive organs (dorsal view). A, Hesperinus rohdendorfi (Hesperinidae). B, Plecia membranifera (Bibionidae). C, Bibio flavihalter (Bibionidae), left vas deferens and testis removed (based on the specimen photographed in Fig. 4A). D, Pachyneura fasciata (Pachyneuridae). acc gl cplx, accessory gland complex; ej dt, ejaculatory duct; tes, testis; vas df, vas deferens. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432334/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF8EB252FCD5FA5EFC11F99B" blockId="7.[826,1442,1483,1566]" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF8EB252FCD5FA5EFC20FA65" box="[826,897,1483,1504]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Testis:</emphasis>
Each testis of 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF8EB252FBD7FA5EFAB5FA64" authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1848" box="[1080,1300,1483,1505]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF8EB252FBD7FA5EFB19FA65" box="[1080,1208,1483,1504]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Hesperinus</emphasis>
Walker
</taxonomicName>
is oval and sack-like, partially collapsed in the material examined.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF8EB252FCD5F9A3FB05F9C9" blockId="7.[826,1188,1590,1612]" box="[826,1188,1590,1612]" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF8EB252FCD5F9A3FC65F9CE" box="[826,964,1590,1611]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Epididymis:</emphasis>
Not differentiated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF8EB252FCD5F9F0FB05F8EA" blockId="7.[826,1442,1636,1903]" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF8EB252FCD5F9F0FC74F9FC" box="[826,981,1636,1658]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="718">Vas deferens:</emphasis>
These ducts are long, slender, and slightly twisted. The ducts extend posteriorly to the base of a large fused accessory gland complex. At their most posterior extension, the vasa deferentia are expanded into kidney-shaped chambers of unknown function (perhaps similar to the inflated sacs in 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF8EB252FAB3F968FCCCF8B7" class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="718" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tipulidae</taxonomicName>
). From these structures, the ducts join medially and arch anteriorly and are continuous with the apex of the accessory gland complex.
</paragraph>
<caption id="D2936E9CFF81B25DFF61F9BEFD16F912" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5432334" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5432334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5432334/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" startId="8.[142,220,1579,1598]" targetBox="[303,1259,197,1547]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph id="86533E14FF81B25DFF61F9BEFD16F912" blockId="8.[142,1422,1579,1687]" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFF61F9BEFF57F9BB" bold="true" box="[142,246,1579,1598]" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Figure 3.</emphasis>
Male internal reproductive organs (dorsal view). A, 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFCF6F9B9FBAFF9BB" box="[793,1038,1579,1598]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rohdendorfi">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFCF6F9B9FBAFF9BB" box="[793,1038,1579,1598]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Hesperinus rohdendorfi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFBF4F9BEFB0AF9BB" box="[1051,1195,1579,1598]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hesperinidae</taxonomicName>
). B, 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFB39F9BEFF16F9D9" authorityName="Hardy &amp; Takahashi" authorityYear="1960" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Plecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="membranifera">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFB39F9BEFF16F9D9" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Plecia membranifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFF28F9DDFE9AF9DE" box="[199,315,1608,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bibionidae</taxonomicName>
). C, 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFE82F9DDFDBAF9DE" authorityName="Hardy &amp; Takahashi" authorityYear="1960" box="[365,539,1608,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Bibio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavihalter">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFE82F9DDFDBAF9DE" box="[365,539,1608,1627]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Bibio flavihalter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFDC4F9DDFD3EF9DE" box="[555,671,1608,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bibionidae</taxonomicName>
), left vas deferens and testis removed (based on the specimen photographed in Fig. 4A). D, 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFE6BF9F3FDF9F9FC" box="[388,600,1638,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Pachyneuridae" genus="Pachyneura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFE6BF9F3FDF9F9FC" box="[388,600,1638,1657]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Pachyneura fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF81B25DFD88F9F3FCA6F9FC" authorityName="Schiner" authorityYear="1864" box="[615,775,1638,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Pachyneuridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="719" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pachyneuridae</taxonomicName>
). acc gl cplx, accessory gland complex; ej dt, ejaculatory duct; tes, testis; vas df, vas deferens. Scale bars = 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF81B25DFF61F975FC56F891" blockId="8.[142,758,1759,1904]" lastBlockId="8.[806,1421,1759,1812]" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFF61F975FDE2F971" box="[142,579,1759,1781]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Accessory gland and seminal vesicle:</emphasis>
A large accessory gland complex is present with at least two distinct chambers visible. The gland remains divided medially throughout its length. No distinct seminal vesicle is present, although the large kidney-shaped expansions of the vasa deferentia may function as storage chambers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF81B25CFCC9F8AEFE7AFF72" blockId="8.[806,1421,1851,1904]" lastBlockId="9.[162,778,195,248]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="720" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF81B25DFCC9F8AEFC4AF8D5" box="[806,1003,1851,1872]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="719">Ejaculatory duct:</emphasis>
At the posterior end of the accessory gland complex, a pair of medially joined ejaculatory ducts exits. They are rather thick walled and extend to the sperm pump.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF80B25CFF4DFE85FE08FE78" blockId="9.[162,779,272,509]" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF80B25CFF4DFE85FCABFEA0" box="[162,778,272,294]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">Ejaculatory apodeme, sperm pump, and aedeagus:</emphasis>
The ejaculatory apodeme is T-shaped in 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF80B25CFD6CFEBAFCA2FEC1" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1848" box="[643,771,303,324]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF80B25CFD6CFEBAFCA2FEC1" box="[643,771,303,324]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">Hesperinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with broad wing-like lateral arms (
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF80B25CFDD5FED8FD7DFEE7" author="Sinclair BJ" box="[570,732,333,355]" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" pagination="53 - 74" refId="ref23502" refString="Sinclair BJ. 2000. Morphology and terminology of Diptera male genitalia. In: Papp L, Darvas B, eds. Contributions to a manual of palaearctic Diptera, Vol. 1 General and applied dipterology. Budapest: Science Herald, 53 - 74." type="book chapter" year="2000">Sinclair, 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 8). The apodeme extends posteriorly to near the apex of the aedeagus. The aedeagus is mostly sclerotized in 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF80B25CFF25FE3FFEEBFE3A" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1848" box="[202,330,426,447]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF80B25CFF25FE3FFEEBFE3A" box="[202,330,426,447]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">Hesperinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a narrow apical phallotrema (or secondary gonopore at the apex of the aedeagus) (
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF80B25CFF45FE72FEEBFE79" author="Sinclair BJ" box="[170,330,487,509]" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" pagination="53 - 74" refId="ref23502" refString="Sinclair BJ. 2000. Morphology and terminology of Diptera male genitalia. In: Papp L, Darvas B, eds. Contributions to a manual of palaearctic Diptera, Vol. 1 General and applied dipterology. Budapest: Science Herald, 53 - 74." type="book chapter" year="2000">Sinclair, 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 11).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86533E14FF80B25CFF4DFD80FD60FD66" blockId="9.[162,778,533,739]" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF80B25CFF4DFD80FEACFDAF" box="[162,269,533,554]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">Remarks:</emphasis>
The male genital tract of 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF80B25CFDD9FD80FD17FDAF" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1848" box="[566,694,533,554]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B498E206FF80B25CFDD9FD80FD17FDAF" box="[566,694,533,554]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="720">Hesperinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here described and illustrated for the first time. The broad lateral plates on the ejaculatory apodeme for the insertion of large muscles appear to be unique among the Bibionomorpha and similar to those observed in some 
<taxonomicName id="41EC4597FF80B25CFF00FD3BFEFDFD41" box="[239,348,686,708]" class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tipulidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF80B25CFE98FD3BFDA8FD46" author="Wood DM" box="[375,521,686,708]" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" pagination="255 - 284" refId="ref24090" refString="Wood DM. 1991. Homology and phylogenetic implications of male genitalia in Diptera. The ground plan. In: Weismann L, Orszagh I, Pont AC, eds. Proceedings of the Second International Congress of Dipterology. The Hague: SPB Academic Publishing, 255 - 284." type="book chapter" year="1991">Wood, 1991</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3a) and lower Brachycera (
<bibRefCitation id="E27D43E5FF80B25CFEDBFD58FD17FD66" author="Sinclair BJ &amp; Cumming JM &amp; Wood DM" box="[308,694,717,739]" pageId="9" pageNumber="720" pagination="407 - 432" refId="ref23601" refString="Sinclair BJ, Cumming JM, Wood DM. 1994. Homology and phylogenetic implications of male genitalia in Diptera - Eremoneura. Entomologica Scandinavica 24 (1993): 407 - 432." type="journal article" year="1994">Sinclair, Cumming &amp; Wood, 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
